##Special Report on the fall of Italy. "This virus is crazy. "

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Liu Dong, thepaper.cn

"This virus is too crazy, it's spreading too fast, you have to be careful, " Maria, an octogenarian Italian, said repeatedly. A month ago, she could never have imagined that the new coronavirus would "pounce" so quickly from her hometown all the way to Brussels, the heart of Europe.

Until mid-february, the outbreak in Europe was quiet after the first confirmed case in Europe was detected in France on January 24. The new coronavirus is like a cunning enemy, lurking quietly across Europe, waiting for the best time. Now, the Viper has come out of its hole. The rapid spread of the new coronavirus across Europe caught everyone off guard.

The turning point came on February 21st in Italy. With the confirmation of the first Italian citizen, the outbreak in Europe's fourth-largest economy is heating up. The outbreak spread from northern Italy, the country's most economically advanced region, and spread across the country in less than a week. March 10, in front of the virus "retreat" in Italy declared the country "closed city.

The new coronaviruses won't just stay in Italy. In just two weeks, thanks to northern Italy's status as Europe's economic, cultural and transportation hub, and the ease of the free movement of people across borders within the European Union, the virus has spread to every country in Europe. Neighboring countries in southern and western Europe were the first to be hit; further north and Britain were soon hit, and even central and eastern Europe, which was relatively far away, was not spared.

As of March 11, the cumulative number of confirmed cases across Europe has exceeded 20,000, with the cumulative death toll exceeding 950, making it the worst affected region outside China. Not only that, new confirmed cases of pneumonia have been reported in almost all countries and regions in Europe. In just 46 days, the new coronavirus has swept across Europe like lightning.

On March 11, who director-general Tan Desai said the epidemic had become a "Pandemic. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Map of European outbreaks. Data as of 19:00 GMT, 11 March. Cartography, thepaper.cn, Gong Wei

With the world's most advanced public health system, it's not too late to start early warning and control measures, why is the new coronavirus still spreading so quickly in Europe? How will Europe respond to the threat of the virus? Next, will more European countries fall as Italy did?

Before contemplating all these unanswered questions, there is the question of how the Italian epidemic began to spiral out of control? If that is not clear, the same tricks that worked in Italy will work in other countries as well.

Looking back on March 10th as the crucial point in the European War of resistance, one can see that the outbreak in Europe did not happen overnight. Behind the "fall" of Italy, there are a series of complicated stories, such as "super-spreading event" , community gathering infection, large-scale mass activity, improper government response and people's psychological contempt.

If the new coronavirus invasion of Europe as a war, the first phase of "imported" defense is the focus of countries; the second phase is to prevent domestic community infection, and Italy became the first lost ground. With the implementation of the National City closure measures, Italy has retreated to avoid the national pandemic outbreak of the last line of defense.

In the coming week, the world will not only be watching Italy. More worrying is that Germany, France, Spain, the United Kingdom and other countries are also under great pressure. If Germany, France and Britain follow Italy's lead, Europe could be plunged into an unprecedented crisis.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Residents quarantined in their homes in northern Italy.

Lurks

March 9 was the day IVA set out on its long-planned trip to China.

A month ago, Finnair, Aivaz's intended flight, canceled all flights to China. After a month of waiting, Aivaz still saw no sign that the flights had resumed. Only this time, because of the outbreak in Europe. He had just finished a meeting in his office at the European Union headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, and when he turned on his computer, a "security alert" message from the European Union had been waiting in his inbox.

Two hours earlier, the Belgian government had reported new cases that day. The number of confirmed cases in Belgium has jumped to nearly 300 in the past week, after a record low of just one in more than a month.

"The situation in Europe is really quite serious right now, " Aivaz told thepaper.cn. On This Day, Italy has just announced the closure of the northern region of the move. The next day, the closure of the city was extended to the whole country. This is unprecedented in the history of the European Union.

Tensions quickly spread thousands of miles away to Brussels, Europe's political capital. On March 9th the monthly plenum of the European Parliament, which was to be held at the Strasbourg in France, was temporarily cancelled and moved to Brussels. Several members of the Italian caucus were absent.

In Aivaz's department, all sociocultural activities have been suspended. Recently, people from Italy or other affected areas need to self-quarantine, the EU also encourages conditional staff to work from home as much as possible.

Yet few people wear masks on the streets of Brussels. Aivaz jokes that this is because after the 2016 terrorist attacks, Belgium passed a law banning anyone from wearing a mask in public. "Of course, you can't even buy a mask in a drugstore. All the stores had a 'out-of-stock masks and other protective items' sign for weeks. "

When the new coronavirus first arrived in Europe more than a month ago, most Europeans thought it was just an epidemic in far-off Asia. Not many Europeans think about what they see on the news, and what will happen to them soon.

On January 21, two days before the city closure in Wuhan, Chen Zhengming, a British epidemiologist and tenured professor at Oxford University, returned to his hometown in Shanghai for the Spring Festival. The outbreak is at its worst in two weeks in China. Although the UK confirmed its first imported case from China in late January, when he returned to the UK in early February, he found few people around him bothered.

January 24, the second day of the siege of Wuhan. France has reported Europe's first imported case, and a 48 year old Chinese diaspora in France from Bordeaux who has just returned from Wuhan has been diagnosed. Two other Chinese nationals who had returned from China were also diagnosed on the same day. This is the earliest officially recorded case of newly diagnosed pneumonia in Europe. Three days later, the German state of Bavaria also reported its first imported case. The number of confirmed cases in Germany has also been growing at a "tepid" pace for some time, with almost all cases linked to the Bavarian company. As of February 26, the cumulative cases in France and Germany were only 12 and 18.

For a month, the new coronavirus seemed to "hide" in Europe. Fewer than 100 cases were reported across Europe between January 24 and February 22. Just when most thought the epidemic might be winding down, the new coronavirus has chosen Italy as the site of a "strong return" outbreak that most would not have thought possible.

The first two imported cases of NCP were detected in Italy on 31 January, after France and Germany. Later, Italy was the first country to declare a state of emergency.

It was only after the development of the epidemic really let Italy "early in the morning, catch a late set. ". On February 21, the "calm" that had lasted nearly a month was broken by the confirmation of an Italian man. The case was later defined by the Italian health authorities as "patient 1" , the cause of the mass infection in the north.

The 38-year-old Italian man, named Mattia, has no travel history in China or a clear history of exposure to high-risk groups, according to media accounts. He developed flu-like symptoms on 14 February, which were reported to the family doctor but not taken seriously, and was admitted on 18 February with what was considered a mild case of pneumonia, which was not serious enough to warrant hospitalization, and was sent home to rest. When he returned to the hospital on February 19, his symptoms had worsened. The diagnosis was made on February 21, when a skilled anesthesiologist insisted that the hospital test him for the new coronavirus infection.

Similar to the early outbreak in Daegu city of South Korea, the "super spread event" caused by "patient 1" outside the surveillance network is one of the important reasons for the escalation of the epidemic. According to the Italian health authorities after incomplete statistics, this "No. 1 patient" at least directly infected more than 10 people, indirectly led to nearly a thousand infections.

On the other hand, the earliest outbreak of epidemic in northern Italy, Milan, Venice is Europe and even the world tourist attractions, perennial visitors. The last week of February is a carnival holiday in most of Europe, and Venice's famous carnival parades have attracted many visitors. All this provides ideal conditions for the spread of the virus.

Chen said it was necessary to go back to the original source of infection and the chain of transmission in order to understand how the Italian epidemic got so out of control. "judging from the extent of the outbreak in Italy, the virus should have spread very early in Italy and the actual number of infections is likely to be higher than the currently announced figures. The new coronavirus has a very tricky thing to do -- it can be transmitted even by people without symptoms, which makes it much more insidious."

Chen suggested that an experience in the war of resistance in another country, Florida, might provide clues to the origins of the Italian epidemic.

The country has confirmed an epidemiological link between the main cases of two apparently unrelated clusters of outbreaks through an antibody test developed by researchers, Ministry of Health said March 1. In this way, they were able to link confirmed cases that appeared to have no source of infection and to clarify the chain of transmission.

Looking back now, Chen says the reasons for Italy's "fall" are complex, but the government's lack of response and people's carelessness are still the main reasons. "although Italy was one of the first European countries to take preventive and control measures, these measures may have given them a blind sense of security, but they were careless. And more importantly, what's really important is what happens with these controls."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Italian Prime Minister Contes called an emergency meeting

Outbursts

On February 22, Italy reported only 22 cumulative cases. By March 11, in just 18 days, that figure had rocketed to 12,462, a 566-fold increase.

Italy, the most economically fragile, politically unstable and aging country in Europe, is now facing a full-scale attack by a new coronavirus.

Italy is no stranger to the plague. The Venetian carnival mask was first invented by the Italians to prevent the spread of the black death in the Middle Ages. This time, however, the carnival masks failed to stop the spread of the new coronavirus.

Italy is also one of the first countries in human history to use the city to prevent the spread of the epidemic. In the face of the highly infectious new pneumonia epidemic, the Italians also became the first part of Europe's declaration "closed" and the first "closed" country. On February 23rd the Italian government declared a blockade on Lombardy and 11 towns in the Veneto region, but the death toll and cases continue to rise, and the virus is spreading far faster than the government is trying to contain it.

"The virus is spreading too fast! It's all over Italy. The government should have acted sooner, " Maria Laura Franciosi, an Italian, told The Paper news with anxiety, "My son is very worried about us. There are a lot of old people in Italy. They are very vulnerable and we just want the virus to go away as the weather warms up. "

There is no scientific basis for Maria's good ideas. The grim reality is that Italians are reminded of the dangers of the epidemic every day.

Maria's sister is in the hard-hit Padua. She told her that the people who had been quarantined at home in the walled-off city were terrified. "Here, people die but there is no funeral. The hospital staff are heavily infected and exhausted, " she said.

On March 9, Italian Prime Minister Contes announced that to prevent the spread of the new pneumonia, Italy would impose a nationwide ban on the city from March 10, and all public gatherings would be banned in Italy, all Sports, including football, will be suspended.

"All of us have to give up something for the benefit of Italy, " Contes said in his speech, "We have to make this decision now, and only if we all work together to adapt to these more stringent measures can we finally do it. "

In an earlier interview with the Italian newspaper La Repubblica, Contes said he had been thinking about what British Prime Minister Winston Churchill said in a speech during World War II: "This is our darkest hour, and we will do it. "

In an interview with the New York Times, Italy's leading virologist, Roberto Burioni, admitted that Italy had underestimated the infectivity of the new coronavirus and that the government needed to act decisively, every Italian needs a responsible response.

Italy, with a population of 60m, is becoming the first major European country to face the twin challenges of such a severe epidemic and draconian measures. Some hospitals are overwhelmed and staff are suffering from widespread infections and are unable to provide care for people over 60. The whole society is also extremely incommensurate to the measure of "sealing off the city" , because stop visiting a prison, 27 Italian prisons even took place riot.

Despite the government's escalating measures, the epidemic has not yet been brought under control. On the other hand, doubts about the decision to "seal off" and the actual effect of its implementation have also emerged in Italian society.

Cui Hongjian, director of the Institute of European Studies at the China Institute of International Studies, said Italy's response itself was questionable. "His approach was neither completely Chinese nor unlike the rest of Europe, but he tried to mix it up and didn't succeed. The early reaction in Italy escalated quickly, but the incomplete closure only amplified the panic and exposed the shortage of medical resources."

Cui Hongjian further pointed out that when the epidemic escalated, the Italians resorted to the measures invented by their ancestors to seal off the city. However, the actual situation today is different. Sealing off the city is not necessarily suitable for European countries with systems like Italy, italy's central government does not have enough executive power or authority. Under such circumstances, taking the old measures will only lead to insufficient public awareness of the epidemic, a large rebound, with negative effects.

As Italy grapples with the epidemic, so do neighboring countries.

Iris v Llnagel, a German journalist, told The Paper that with the outbreak in Italy, multiple cases of the disease have been found in many parts of Germany. At the same time, confirmed cases unrelated to the Italian epidemic were found in more regions, some of which were also linked to mass gatherings at local Mardi gras events.

These phenomena are not confined to Germany. In just two weeks, Germany, France, Spain and other countries have broken 1,000 cases; more than 100 are Switzerland, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, Sweden, Belgium, Norway, Austria, Denmark and other countries. Across Europe, the new coronavirus is spreading rapidly in almost all countries, with many countries already experiencing community-based transmission without a clear source of infection.

Cui Hongjian believes that the spread of the new Crown Epidemic in Europe is so rapid that it is not only related to the geographical closeness of European countries, but also highlights the fact that the epidemic prevention throughout Europe is full of "holes. ". "although it looks like Italy is losing, it's hard to say that it's all Italy. If the European refugee crisis of 2015 exposed Europe's vulnerability to refugees, it now appears that Europe is also vulnerable to the virus."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers wait at Milan railway station in Italy

Diffused

Zhang Lei, a teacher at Belgium's Free University, notes that the number of cases has increased since many Belgians returned from the Carnival holiday more than a week ago. Almost every day since last week, that number has doubled.

"You can't buy Belgian masks or alcohol or anything like that anymore. Every morning when I post the number of new cases that day on my facebook page, my Chinese friends ask me, Zhang Lei, are you scared? To be honest, I'm a little scared, and I'm worried about the government's ability to protect us if an epidemic like the one in Wuhan happens in Belgium,"said Zhang Lei, who has lived in Belgium for decades, but degrees and measures differ, and there are many reasons for this.

"They can't do what China has done, and the government doesn't have the ability or the need to do it; there's only one nucleic acid test in Brussels, and the second one arrived today; and there are strict conditions for testing the government, where you have to have symptoms, and then you have to have a history of exposure, before you can call your family doctor, and the hospital will send someone over to check it, " she said.

The Belgian government believes that there has been no large-scale human-to-human transmission in the country, describing the outbreak as a "limited, small-scale, distributed group infection" .

Eris, who lives in Leipzig, Germany, told thepaper.cn that although the current outbreak in Germany is still mainly in specific areas, the situation is changing.

"You can see that people's lives are being affected and changed. I have friends who are afraid to take public transportation and feel dangerous. People are afraid because of the change in the number of cases, people are afraid that what is happening in Italy will happen in Germany,"she said.

Iris said the government began to strongly encourage people to wash their hands frequently, not recommended meet and shake hands etiquette. "people are starting to worry that people are going to the shops last week to stock up; a lot of big events have been cancelled, such as the book fair in Leipzig next week. In the convention city of Hanover, most events were postponed from April to August. But the football match is still going on and some of the government's actions are confusing,"she said.

Yet few people still wear masks in Germany, which iris explains is partly because of cultural reasons, people are not used to wearing masks, and the government tells people that wearing masks does not protect people from infection.

If the outbreak escalates, will Germany close the city like Italy? Iris thinks it's hard to say. "If the city is closed, the impact will be huge and local governments will have to deal with all the problems that come with it. The epidemic has not yet reached that stage. The main theme in Germany now is not the closure of the city, but the cancellation of events for more than 1,000 people."

While the government's response to the outbreak is not to be taken lightly, German society is increasingly divided. Some think the response has been overdone, while others think the government has not done enough. "In retrospect, the German government could have done more to prevent [ the outbreak ] in the first place. At this stage, the government tells us that the virus is not dangerous and that Germany can handle it. But I don't know if it escalates,"Iris said.

AIVAZ, who works at the European Union's headquarters in Brussels, is representative of the "optimists" . He told The Paper that all Estonian citizens have received emails from the government asking people who have been to affected and high risk areas to stay home for two weeks, but he himself is not nervous about the outbreak.

"Now that the virus has arrived, shutting down the schools won't help, it will only affect normal life and everything will have to be rearranged. There's a school in Estonia that's closed, but I don't think parents can keep their kids at home, there's a good chance they'll still come out,"he said.

Chinese and European governments and the public's different understanding of the new coronavirus is also an important reason for the different attitudes towards the epidemic.

Zhang Lei told The Paper that not long ago she was talking to some European politicians about the epidemic. The leader of a local political party told her they did not think the outbreak was that serious and there was no need to panic. The editor-in-chief of a local newspaper in Brussels said that while he was horrified by the rapid spread of the new coronavirus, such concerns were not reflected in daily life and business as usual.

Cui further pointed out that China and the European understanding of the epidemic to a large extent because of their different reference. "The Chinese reference is the 2003 SARS [ Atypical pneumonia ] and the European reference is the flu, so the attitude and reaction is very different. "

"To be honest, I don't have much confidence in the Belgian government's response to the pandemic. If there is a major outbreak, the government will have a hard time dealing with it. My worst case scenario is that if there's an outbreak in Europe, the safest place is back home,"Zhang Lei said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medics work at a medical facility in Italy

A pandemic?

Today, for most European countries, the focus of prevention and control of the epidemic in addition to imports from Asian countries, but also a heavy pressure from within Europe to prevent and control.

Cui believes that if the new European crown fight against disease is divided into three stages: the first stage is to prevent imported cases; the second stage is to prevent domestic community transmission; and the third stage is to avoid domestic and European pandemics.

"for European countries, an important principle is the balance between prevention and control of the epidemic and economic performance, taking into account the impact of secondary disasters on society. Italy initially hoped that in the prevention and control second stage, can block the epidemic the development, also can maintain the contact with the outside world. However, the facts proved that they did not succeed, and then had to resort to a final and comprehensive blockade,"Cui Hongjian said.

At present, Germany and France have entered the second phase of epidemic prevention and control. Cui Hongjian believes that the main strategy at this stage in both countries is to delay and control the spread of the epidemic in the community as far as possible, so as to avoid a centralized outbreak.

He went on, "because of the nature of the European National System, the central government is effectively caught between local government and the EU. Down the line, most of the time they have to coordinate with local governments, providing information and not being able to get a handle on how to respond. Up, the nature of the EU is that it is often co-ordinated and can not easily make any decisions, and the principle of free movement is a No-go area."

"In the worst case, if Germany and France also 'fall' , they could lead the push to stop the free movement of people within the EU, but it's hard to imagine, " he said.

Christiane Drosten, a leading German virologist known as "Zhong Nanshan" , made a similar point in a recent interview with the German media: Germany can not copy the Chinese experience, but it is necessary to continuously observe the follow-up development of virus transmission and take corresponding countermeasures in time. Germany is well placed to deal with the outbreak. Interventions should be attempted through targeted interventions where the cost-benefit ratio is appropriate to delay large-scale transmission of the virus (especially in young and middle-aged populations) .

The French government also refuses to take comprehensive preventive measures similar to those in Italy. "We are still in the early stages of this epidemic, " French President Maqueron said after a March 10 visit to the emergency call center in Paris. "We have a plan and we are ready. "

For the time being, there seems to be little consensus in Europe on how to deal with the epidemic, and much fragmentation. Cui said the difference in thinking patterns between China and the West also determines different strategies for epidemic prevention and control. "Europeans tend to assume the worst and then extrapolate back to what to do now. "there is a natural order of things, and European countries tend to look at the social costs and see which way the epidemic might go before taking action. "

Regarding the future trend of the European epidemic, Chen Zhengming said that, "I am not that pessimistic personally and I don't think there will be a situation like that in Italy. Let's hope they learn from Italy's mistakes. But things are bound to get worse in the next week or two. What worries me is that countries are not doing enough to prevent and control it. Hopefully by Easter in April, things will be clearer."

On March 11th World Health Organization's Chief Executive, Tan Desai, said a "pandemic" caused by a coronavirus was the first in history, but that all countries had a chance to change the course of the pandemic.

There is no sign yet that the spreading epidemic across Europe is ending. The real test for Europe will be how to win the battle against the new coronavirus.
